<BaseLayout title="How to measure for goalie leg pads | Goalie Gear Fit" description="Measure floor-to-knee and ankle-to-knee accurately for goalie leg-pad sizing." canonicalPath="/guides/how-to-measure-goalie-pads" {breadcrumbs}><Breadcrumbs items={breadcrumbs}/><article class="content"><h1>How to measure for goalie leg pads</h1><p>Sizing starts with the exact measurement method named by the manufacturer chart. Floor-to-knee (FTK) and ankle-to-knee (ATK) are different inputs and must never be converted into one another.</p><section class="card"><h2>What you need</h2><ul><li>A flexible tape measure marked in inches or centimetres.</li><li>A firm chair or bench where the goalie can sit naturally.</li><li>A helper to keep the tape straight and read the endpoint.</li></ul></section><section class="card"><h2>Seated measurement steps</h2><ol><li>Wear thin clothing and sit with skates off, feet flat and knees bent naturally.</li><li>Locate the centre of the kneecap. For ATK, start at the ankle bone and measure straight to that centre point.</li><li>For FTK, stand only if the reviewed chart calls for it; measure vertically from the floor to the kneecap centre.</li><li>Record the method, value and unit together. Repeat once before using a chart.</li></ol></section><section class="card"><h2>Common mistakes</h2><ul><li>Measuring to the top or bottom of the kneecap instead of its centre.</li><li>Following the curve of the shin rather than the specified straight line.</li><li>Using ATK in a floor-to-knee table or rounding across a published gap.</li></ul><p><strong>No tape?</strong> Do not estimate from height or age. Wait until you can measure, or ask a qualified retailer/fitter to measure.</p></section><p><a href="/guides/thigh-rise-and-fit-check">Next: thigh rise and physical fit checks</a></p></article></BaseLayout>
